### Transform data in Code node using JavaScript

Source: https://context7.com/n8n-io/n8n-docs/llms.txt

Implements custom JavaScript logic in n8n Code node for data transformation and calculations. Supports both 'Run Once for All Items' and 'Run Once for Each Item' modes with access to input data, other nodes, workflow variables, environment variables, and Luxon for date operations. Includes error handling and async operations.

```javascript
// Run Once for All Items mode - process all items together
// Access all input items
const items = $input.all();

// Transform and return new items
const results = items.map(item => {
  return {
    json: {
      originalName: item.json.name,
      processedName: item.json.name.toUpperCase(),
      timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),
      itemCount: items.length
    }
  };
});

return results;

// ---

// Run Once for Each Item mode - process items individually
// Access current item
const currentItem = $input.item;
const data = $json; // shorthand for $input.item.json

// Return transformed item
return {
  json: {
    ...data,
    processed: true,
    calculatedValue: data.price * data.quantity
  }
};

// ---

// Access data from other nodes
const webhookData = $('Webhook').first().json;
const allHttpItems = $('HTTP Request').all();
const lastItem = $('Previous Node').last();

// Access workflow variables
const apiUrl = $vars.API_BASE_URL;

// Access environment variables (self-hosted)
const secret = $env.MY_SECRET;

// Access execution context
const executionId = $execution.id;
const isManualRun = $execution.mode === 'manual';
const workflowName = $workflow.name;

// Working with dates using Luxon
const now = DateTime.now();
const futureDate = now.plus({ days: 30 });
const formatted = futureDate.toFormat('yyyy-MM-dd');

// Error handling
try {
  const result = riskyOperation();
  return [{ json: { success: true, data: result } }];
} catch (error) {
  return [{ json: { success: false, error: error.message } }];
}

// Async operations with promises
const response = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data');
const data = await response.json();
return [{ json: data }];
```

--------------------------------

### Access and transform data using n8n expressions

Source: https://context7.com/n8n-io/n8n-docs/llms.txt

Demonstrates n8n expression syntax using {{ }} notation for dynamic parameter values. Supports accessing previous node data, nested JSON, JavaScript operations, workflow metadata, date/time manipulation with Luxon, and JMESPath queries. Expressions enable data transformation without writing full code blocks.

```javascript
// Access data from previous node
{{ $json.body.city }}

// Access nested JSON data
{{ $json['user']['profile']['email'] }}

// Use JavaScript in expressions
{{ $json.price * 1.1 }}

// String manipulation
{{ $json.name.toUpperCase() }}

// Conditional expression
{{ $json.status === 'active' ? 'Enabled' : 'Disabled' }}

// Access data from a specific node by name
{{ $('HTTP Request').item.json.response }}

// Get all items from a node
{{ $('Webhook').all() }}

// Access workflow metadata
{{ $workflow.name }}
{{ $workflow.id }}

// Access execution metadata
{{ $execution.id }}
{{ $execution.mode }}

// Date/time with Luxon
{{ DateTime.now().toISO() }}
{{ DateTime.fromISO($json.date).plus({ days: 7 }).toFormat('yyyy-MM-dd') }}

// IIFE for complex logic
{{(()=>{
  let end = DateTime.fromISO('2024-03-13');
  let start = DateTime.fromISO('2024-02-13');
  let diffInMonths = end.diff(start, 'months');
  return diffInMonths.toObject();
})()

// JMESPath for querying JSON
{{ $jmespath($json.users, "[?age > `30`].name") }}
```

--------------------------------

### Access n8n workflow data and metadata using built-in JavaScript methods

Source: https://context7.com/n8n-io/n8n-docs/llms.txt

This JavaScript code illustrates n8n's built-in methods and variables for accessing input data, data from other nodes, workflow metadata, execution context, environment variables, and utility functions. Examples include `$input`, `$json`, `$binary`, `$('Node Name')`, `$workflow`, `$execution`, `$env`, `$vars`, `DateTime` objects, and other utility variables. A complete data access pattern demonstrates how to combine these for practical use within n8n Code nodes.

```javascript
// Current node input methods
$input.item          // Current item being processed
$input.all()         // All input items
$input.first()       // First input item
$input.last()        // Last input item
$json                // Shorthand for $input.item.json
$binary              // Shorthand for $input.item.binary

// Access other nodes' data
$('Node Name').item              // Paired item from named node
$('Node Name').first()           // First item from named node
$('Node Name').last()            // Last item from named node
$('Node Name').all()             // All items from named node
$('Node Name').itemMatching(0)   // Item at specific index

// Workflow and execution metadata
$workflow.id              // Workflow ID
$workflow.name            // Workflow name
$workflow.active          // Whether workflow is active
$execution.id             // Current execution ID
$execution.mode           // 'manual', 'trigger', or 'webhook'
$execution.resumeUrl      // URL to resume waiting execution

// Environment and variables
$env.VARIABLE_NAME        // Environment variable (self-hosted)
$vars.variableName        // Workflow variable

// Date and time (Luxon)
$now                      // Current DateTime
$today                    // Start of today
DateTime.now()            // Current DateTime
DateTime.fromISO('2024-01-15')
DateTime.fromFormat('15/01/2024', 'dd/MM/yyyy')

// Utility methods
$runIndex                 // Current run index in loop
$itemIndex                // Current item index
$nodeVersion              // Version of current node
$position                 // Position in workflow

// Example: Complete data access pattern
const webhookBody = $('Webhook').first().json.body;
const allRecords = $('Database Query').all();
const executionId = $execution.id;
const apiKey = $vars.EXTERNAL_API_KEY;
const currentDate = DateTime.now().toFormat('yyyy-MM-dd');

return [{
  json: {
    webhookData: webhookBody,
    recordCount: allRecords.length,
    executionId,
    processedDate: currentDate
  }
}];
```

### Schedule Trigger node > Node parameters > Custom (Cron) interval

Source: https://github.com/n8n-io/n8n-docs/blob/main/docs/integrations/builtin/core-nodes/n8n-nodes-base.scheduletrigger/index.md

For the **Custom (Cron) interval**, enter a custom cron **Expression** to set the schedule for the trigger. To generate a Cron expression, you can use crontab guru (https://crontab.guru). Paste the Cron expression that you generated using crontab guru in the **Expression** field in n8n.

--------------------------------

### Schedule Trigger node common issues > Invalid cron expression

Source: https://github.com/n8n-io/n8n-docs/blob/main/docs/integrations/builtin/core-nodes/n8n-nodes-base.scheduletrigger/common-issues.md

The invalid cron expression error occurs when you set **Trigger Interval** to **Custom (Cron)** and n8n doesn't understand your cron expression. This may mean that there is a mistake in your cron expression or that you're using an incompatible syntax. To debug, verify that your cron expression follows the correct syntax and that it (after removing the seconds column) validates on crontab guru.

